The very first dish I presented at @Padaek 13 years ago was this salad. My childhood nostalgia food I never forget. 

My mom usually took me on occasionally to eat this Lao specialty at the food stall in the town along the Mekong River divide Laos and Thailand.  This particular dish was call Naem/NamTha Deua.  As I recalled the only place we can get it back in the 70's was only at one location.  This is why in my opinion that Naem Khao was originated in Baan Tha Deua, Vientiane,  Laos.

This dish was creating from left over Jamine rice mixed with smashed galangal, lemongrass, makrut lime leave, garlic, shallot, ground pork as optional,  egg for binding then formed into small balls(size of tennis ball), deep fried.  Before eaten, broken it down then toss in fresh herbs, peanut, cured pork, pork skin, fish sauce and lime juice. Served with lettuce and varieties of fresh herbs.

Pon Paa is of my family favorite dish.  It's  perfect with side vegetables and sticky rice.  I'll be serving this dry version of Pon Paa for Lao New Year special. 

HUMBLED FOOD FOR THOUGHT: Pon Paa was very common in most Lao house hold in my home town.  It's a classic dish made with steamed catfish with galangal and fermented fish sauce, then smashed it in mortar pestle with charred garlic, shallot, fish stock and loaded with charred green eggplant to feed large family.  In fact,  it was our survivor food.

#laonewyear #celebration #respect #culture #laofood #laofoodmovement

Lactic acid fermentation method is very common in Laos to preserve meat, fish and vegetables.  As many of you might had Muu Som(2nd picture) at @thipkhaodc.  Muu Som made with pork belly marinated with cooked sticky rice, garlic and sea salt.  In Laos typically cook straight on the grilled before seeving.  But I decided to served with some twist by tossing in the wok for extra layers of umami, smoky and textured with black wood fungus.

ສົ້ມໝູ Som Muu, basically same fermentation as Muu Som that made with ground pork and pork skin wrapped with banana leave then grill as "Knab" style.  Knab Som Muu ແນບສົ້ມຫມູ will be one of the array this Thursday.

In the honor of my grandmother who taught me early on how to cook sticky rice, stuffed salted fish in the clay jar to make fermented fish sauce we called PADAEK.  Beside my mother, she was one strong woman who inspired me everyday. 

This humbled salad she taught me with left over sticky rice, dried in the sun for couple days, puffed in hot oil, then smashed with mortar pestle and tossed with minced grilled fish, banana blossom, green bean, beam sprout and lots of herbs, serve with sweet and sour fish sauce.  It may look like the popular Naem Khao but it's different.  This type of salad became our family favorite that feed our big family.

Can't wait to showcase this PUN NAEM PAA on the menu at @padaekdc new location soon.🙏
